<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="163" pageId="4" pageNumber="162" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1703,2016]" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1847,1872]" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[335,505,1847,1872]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="4" pageNumber="162" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[335,505,1847,1872]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">Scalarispongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cushion-shaped with tubular projections of thin walls and surface irregularly microconulose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1703,2016]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="163" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,460,1919,1944]" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">External Morphology</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[478,546,1919,1944]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1874,1896]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scalarispongia tubulata sp. nov. (A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A – B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A–B). Thick encrusting to cushion-shaped, rounded in the upper part and flat near the base. 
<typeStatus box="[321,425,1955,1980]" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">Holotype</typeStatus>
measures 5.5 x 
<quantity box="[620,699,1955,1980]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="162" unit="cm" value="2.5">2.5 cm</quantity>
(width x height) and 
<typeStatus box="[958,1054,1956,1980]" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">paratype</typeStatus>
measures 6.0 x 
<quantity box="[1249,1328,1955,1980]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="162" unit="cm" value="1.5">1.5 cm</quantity>
(width x height). The color is light brown in ethanol. Color 
<emphasis box="[750,828,1992,2015]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="162">in vivo</emphasis>
unknown. Tubular projections are scattered over the surface up to 
<quantity box="[305,370,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="163" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
high. These projections are fragile and have thin walls. The oscula are located on top of tubes with 
<quantity box="[208,301,188,212]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="163" unit="mm" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3 mm</quantity>
in diameter. The surface is irregularly microconulose. The consistency is firm and compressible.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="163" targetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1874,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,278,1874,1896]" pageId="5" pageNumber="163">FIGURE 4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[287,535,1874,1896]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="5" pageNumber="163" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="tubulata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[287,535,1874,1896]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="163">Scalarispongia tubulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[544,627,1874,1895]" pageId="5" pageNumber="163" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[544,627,1874,1895]" pageId="5" pageNumber="163">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A–B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="164" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1365]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,151,176]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[317,383,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1874,1896]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scalarispongia tubulata sp. nov. (A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A – B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
C–D) A network of concentrically laminated primary and secondary fibers forms the skeleton (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1874,1896]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scalarispongia tubulata sp. nov. (A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A – B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
C, D). Primary fibers are scattered, axially or totally cored mostly by foreign spicules and debris. Granular pith is not visible. The secondary fiber reticulum is well developed, branching and regular (
<figureCitation box="[1172,1240,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1874,1896]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scalarispongia tubulata sp. nov. (A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A – B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
C). All secondary fibers are uncored and occasionally form secondary webs, which are more frequent in the skeleton of the tubes than of the sponge body. In some regions, the secondary fibers connect the primary fibers almost in right angles. Few pseudo-tertiary fibers could be observed, always restricted to the meshes of the secondary reticulum (
<figureCitation box="[1330,1401,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1874,1896]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scalarispongia tubulata sp. nov. (A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A – B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
D). Sometimes the fibers are perforated by spicules arranged transversally inside them. Primary fibers are 60–92–140 µm in diameter (n = 12), secondary fibers are 30–64–150 µm in diameter (n = 11) and pseudo-tertiary fibers are 
<date box="[151,262,439,464]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" value="1950-10-25">10–25–50</date>
µm in diameter (n = 12). The meshes are circular to oval, 37–82.5–150 µm in diameter, and the secondary webs measure 120–165–230 µm in width (n = 6).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1365]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,313,511,536]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Histology</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[328,394,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1874,1896]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scalarispongia tubulata sp. nov. (A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A – B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
E–F). The ectosome is fibrous, with a layer of elongated microgranular cells, debris and sand grains dispersed outside the fibers (
<figureCitation box="[552,621,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1874,1896]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scalarispongia tubulata sp. nov. (A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A – B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
E). The choanocyte chambers are diplodal, spherical to oval, with 12.5– 24.4–40 µm in diameter (
<figureCitation box="[438,506,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1874,1896]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scalarispongia tubulata sp. nov. (A) Holotype (MNRJ 17620); (B) Paratype (UFSPOR 223); (C) Reticulated skeleton of isolated spongin fibers, showing a cored primary fiber (pf) and an uncored secondary reticulum (sr); (D). Elements of fiber skeleton: cored primary fibers (pf), uncored secondary fibers (sf), pseudo-tertiary fibers (ptf) and secondary web (sw); (E) Cross section of the fiber skeleton; (F) Histological section. Scale bars: A – B, 1 cm; C, 205 µm; D, 82 µm; E, 550 µm, F, 250 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/164564/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
F; n = 15). However, these measurements are probably biased because the fixation in ethanol was not adequate for histological analysis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1365]" box="[199,1353,655,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,502,655,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Bathymetry and Ecology.</emphasis>
The specimens were found at 
<quantity box="[844,900,656,680]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" unit="m" value="30.0">30 m</quantity>
depth, associated to hydroids and algae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1365]" box="[199,1272,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1324562846" box="[199,1272,692,717]" country="Brazil" location="Sergipe" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Sergipe">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,516,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Geographical distribution.</emphasis>
Only known from northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[876,949,692,717]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion box="[959,1044,692,717]" country="Brazil" name="Sergipe" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Sergipe</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1099,1191,692,717]" country="Brazil" name="Alagoas" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Alagoas</collectingRegion>
States.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1160,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1365]" box="[199,1160,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName box="[459,553,727,752]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="tubulata">
<emphasis box="[459,553,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">tubulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the tubular projections typical of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="164" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1365]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,764,789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[324,597,764,789]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="tubulata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[324,597,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Scalarispongia tubulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[608,700,764,789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[608,700,764,789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
was allocated in this genus due to the unarmoured surface and regular reticulation with secondary webs, as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cook" box="[779,1069,799,824]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Cook, S. de C. &amp; Bergquist, P. R. (2000) Two new genera and five new species of the ' Cacospongia ' group (Porifera, Demospongiae, Dictyoceratida). Zoosystema, 22 (2), 383 - 400." type="journal article" year="2000">Cook &amp; Bergquist (2000)</bibRefCitation>
. However, the new species has a well-developed secondary reticulum similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[687,835,836,859]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Cacospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[687,835,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Cacospongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook" box="[941,1080,836,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Cook, S. de C. (2007) Clarification of dictyoceratid taxonomic characters, and the determination of genera. In: Custodio, M. R., Lobo-Hajdu, G., Hajdu, E. &amp; Muricy, G. (Eds.), Porifera Research: Biodiversity, Innovation and Sustainability. Serie Livros 28. Museu Nacional, Rio de Janeiro, pp. 265 - 274." type="journal article" year="2007">Cook, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Compared to the 
<typeStatus box="[1298,1346,837,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmidt 1862" authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1862" box="[151,563,871,896]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Cacospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="mollior">
<emphasis box="[151,392,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Cacospongia mollior</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt" box="[401,563,871,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Schmidt, O. (1862) Die Spongien des Adriatischen Meeres. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig, 82 pp." type="book" year="1862">Schmidt 1862</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, the secondary fiber skeleton of 
<taxonomicName box="[945,1218,871,896]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="tubulata" status="sp. nov">
<emphasis box="[945,1218,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Scalarispongia tubulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1228,1312,872,895]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" rank="species">sp. nov</taxonomicNameLabel>
is regular, with many oval meshes and secondary webs between the primary fibers, whereas the secondary reticulum of 
<taxonomicName class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Cacospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="mollior">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">C. mollior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is irregular and secondary webs are absent (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook" box="[728,1008,943,968]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Cook, S. de C. &amp; Bergquist, P. R. (2000) Two new genera and five new species of the ' Cacospongia ' group (Porifera, Demospongiae, Dictyoceratida). Zoosystema, 22 (2), 383 - 400." type="journal article" year="2000">Cook &amp; Bergquist, 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cook" box="[1018,1154,943,968]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Cook, S. de C. (2007) Clarification of dictyoceratid taxonomic characters, and the determination of genera. In: Custodio, M. R., Lobo-Hajdu, G., Hajdu, E. &amp; Muricy, G. (Eds.), Porifera Research: Biodiversity, Innovation and Sustainability. Serie Livros 28. Museu Nacional, Rio de Janeiro, pp. 265 - 274." type="journal article" year="2007">Cook, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The regular reticulation and secondary webs of the new species are more similar to the 
<typeStatus box="[849,897,981,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1021,1191,980,1005]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1021,1191,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Scalarispongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmidt, 1862" authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1862" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="scalaris">
<emphasis box="[1204,1320,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">S. scalaris</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Schmidt, O. (1862) Die Spongien des Adriatischen Meeres. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig, 82 pp." type="book" year="1862">Schmidt, 1862</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1365]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
Only two species of 
<taxonomicName box="[427,597,1052,1077]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[427,597,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Scalarispongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and two of 
<taxonomicName box="[727,875,1052,1075]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Cacospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[727,875,1052,1075]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Cacospongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were recorded from the Tropical 
<collectingRegion box="[1248,1339,1053,1076]" country="American Samoa" name="Western" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Western</collectingRegion>
Atlantic Ocean. 
<taxonomicName authority="Lamarck, 1814" authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1814" box="[238,743,1087,1112]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="linteiformis">
<emphasis box="[238,545,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Scalarispongia linteiformis</emphasis>
(Lamarck, 1814)
</taxonomicName>
was recorded from Greater Antilles and is known only from the original description. It has a ramose shape, thus clearly differing from 
<taxonomicName box="[1052,1327,1124,1149]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="tubulata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1052,1327,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Scalarispongia tubulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1340,1436,1124,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1340,1436,1124,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
<taxonomicName authority="Boury-Esnault, 1973" authorityName="Boury-Esnault" authorityYear="1973" box="[151,662,1159,1184]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cincta">
<emphasis box="[151,399,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Scalarispongia cincta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Boury-Esnault" box="[416,654,1159,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Boury-Esnault, N. (1973) Resultats scientifiques des campagnes de la ' Calypso': Campagne de la ' Calypso' au large des cotes atlantiques de l'Amerique du Sud (1961 - 1962). I. 29. Spongiaires. Annales de l'Institut Oceanographique, 49 (Supplement 10), 263 - 295." type="journal article" year="1973">Boury-Esnault, 1973</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is transferred here to 
<taxonomicName box="[920,1020,1159,1184]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Thorecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[920,1020,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Thorecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above). 
<taxonomicName authority="Polejaeff, 1884" authorityName="Polejaeff" authorityYear="1884" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Cacospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="amorpha">
<emphasis box="[1177,1436,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Cacospongia amorpha</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Polejaeff" box="[151,328,1196,1221]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Polejaeff, N. (1884) Report on the Keratosa collected by H. M. S. ' Challenger' during the years 1873 - 1876. Reports on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. ' Challenger', 1873 - 1876, Zoology, 11, 1 - 88." type="journal article" year="1884">Poléjaeff, 1884</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Polejaeff, 1884" authorityName="Polejaeff" authorityYear="1884" box="[395,798,1196,1221]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Cacospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="levis">
<emphasis box="[395,608,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Cacospongia levis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Polejaeff" box="[621,798,1196,1221]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Polejaeff, N. (1884) Report on the Keratosa collected by H. M. S. ' Challenger' during the years 1873 - 1876. Reports on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. ' Challenger', 1873 - 1876, Zoology, 11, 1 - 88." type="journal article" year="1884">Poléjaeff, 1884</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
were described for the Brazilian coast. 
<taxonomicName class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Cacospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="amorpha">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Cacospongia amorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a massive to rounded shape, oscules flush with the surface and larger, more spaced conules; 
<taxonomicName box="[1351,1436,1231,1256]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Cacospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="levis">
<emphasis box="[1351,1436,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">C. levis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a massive shape, smooth surface and black external color (
<bibRefCitation author="Polejaeff" box="[873,1052,1268,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Polejaeff, N. (1884) Report on the Keratosa collected by H. M. S. ' Challenger' during the years 1873 - 1876. Reports on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. ' Challenger', 1873 - 1876, Zoology, 11, 1 - 88." type="journal article" year="1884">Poléjaeff, 1884</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Muricy" box="[1065,1285,1268,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" refString="Muricy, G., Lopes, D. A., Hajdu, E., Carvalho, M. S., Moraes, F. C., Klautau, M., Menegola, C. &amp; Pinheiro, U. (2011) Catalogue of Brazilian Porifera. Serie Livros. nº 46. Museu Nacional, Rio de Janeiro, 212 pp." type="book" year="2011">
Muricy 
<emphasis box="[1156,1214,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">et al.</emphasis>
, 2011
</bibRefCitation>
figs. 8C–D). 
<taxonomicName box="[151,420,1303,1328]" class="Demospongiae" family="Thorectidae" genus="Scalarispongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="tubulata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,420,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Scalarispongia tubulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[428,517,1303,1328]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[428,517,1303,1328]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from these species by its cushion shape, tubular oscula and microconulose surface (Tab. 1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
